<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15417">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b> The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and
      downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Public%20Health.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15444">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15444 mb-requirement-id-15448">
        (a) Explain what public health is. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/t_eWESXTnic" target="_blank"
          >What Is Public Health?? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/5aww-Bpgkf4" target="_blank"
          >What Is Public Health? Crash Course Public Health #1 (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/uKe1KNi3YgI" target="_blank"
          >Why Public Health Matters (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15444 mb-requirement-id-15449">
        (b) Explain how Escherichia coli (E. coli), tetanus, AIDS, encephalitis,
        salmonellosis, Lyme disease, and coronavirus (COVID-19) are contracted.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Zw7oWOvOjiQ" target="_blank"
          >Food Safety: Avoiding E. coli (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/g0cd6iVfNbw" target="_blank"
          >What Is Tetanus and How Do You Get It? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/7XT8dBmJdMo" target="_blank"
          >Salmonella (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ENmVXtwsKE8" target="_blank"
          >5 Tips to Prevent Tick Bites and Getting Lyme Disease (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/oqFn6AHoJZQ" target="_blank"
          >How the COVID-19 Virus Is Transmitted (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15444 mb-requirement-id-15450">
        (c) Choose any four of the following diseases and explain how each one
        is contracted and possibly prevented: gonorrhea, West Nile virus,
        botulism, influenza, syphilis, hepatitis, emphysema, meningitis, herpes,
        or lead poisoning. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/AL6V4eB-mbI" target="_blank"
          >West Nile Story (West Nile Virus Prevention Rap) (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/2v3dgup6n7c" target="_blank"
          >6 Types of Botulism: Food, Infant, Wound &amp; More Explained!
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/qq8tq4AEpxU" target="_blank"
          >How Does the Flu Spread? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Zc6MSB622SE" target="_blank"
          >Emphysema, Explained in 90 Seconds (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/FHLWnlrmKNg" target="_blank"
          >The Signs and Symptoms of Meningitis (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/L-crRQLn_p0" target="_blank"
          >Why Lead Poisoning Is a Danger to Your Child's Health | UNICEF
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15444 mb-requirement-id-15451">
        (d) For all 10 diseases from 1(c), explain the type or form of the
        disease (viral, bacterial, environmental, toxin), any possible vectors
        for transmission, ways to help prevent exposure or the spread of
        infection, and available treatments. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/uNc99BEaJLs" target="_blank"
          >How West Nile Virus Is Transmitted (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/rI9ysEaJzVs" target="_blank"
          >What Is Botulism? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/WSZEcpti2i0" target="_blank"
          >Flu Virus 101 (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/copd/about/index.html" target="_blank"
          >About COPD or Emphysema (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.cdc.gov/meningitis/about/index.html"
          target="_blank"
          >Meningitis (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.cdc.gov/lead-prevention/about/index.html"
          target="_blank"
          >Lead Poisoning (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15418">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15418 mb-requirement-id-15419">
        (a) Explain the meaning of <em>immunization.</em> <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/4SKmAlQtAj8" target="_blank"
          >Vaccines 101: How Vaccines Work (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/z0kfdZ8o_j4" target="_blank"
          >How mRNA Vaccines Actually Work | Inside the Vaccine (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15418 mb-requirement-id-15420">
        (b) Name eight diseases against which a young child should be immunized,
        two diseases against which everyone should be reimmunized periodically,
        and one immunization everyone should receive annually. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/zaXVO4hHld8" target="_blank"
          >What You Need To Know About Childhood Immunizations (podcast)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/1yf7uEnEU6o" target="_blank"
          >Vaccines for Children Program: 30 Years of Protecting Children
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15418 mb-requirement-id-15421">
        (c) Using the list of diseases and conditions in requirement 1, discuss
        with your counselor those which currently have no immunization
        available.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15445">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Discuss the importance of safe drinking water in terms of the spread of
      disease. Then, demonstrate two ways for making water safe to drink that
      can be used while at camp. In your demonstration, explain how dishes and
      utensils should be washed, dried, and kept sanitary at home and in camp.
      <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/GlTdIRxpxAQ" target="_blank"
        >Waterborne Diseases | Waterborne Pathogens | Public Health and Water
        Safety | Prevention &amp; Control (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/DIZz3iiZ2TY" target="_blank"
        >The Best Way to Filter Water While Backpacking (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/4tNLdcjBlQc" target="_blank"
        >How to Wash Dishes at Camp (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15446">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Explain what a vector is and how insects and rodents can be controlled in
      your home, in your community, and at camp. Tell why this is important. In
      your discussion, explain which vectors can be easily controlled by
      individuals and which ones require long-term, collective action. <br /><i
        >Resource:</i
      >
      <a href="https://youtu.be/0xSUITkRvbA" target="_blank"
        >WHO Vector Borne Disease Animation (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15422">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      With your parent or guardian's and counselor's approval, do ONE of the
      following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15422 mb-requirement-id-15423">
        (a) Visit a municipal wastewater treatment facility or a solid-waste
        management operation in your community.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15423 mb-requirement-id-15424">
        (1) Describe how the facility safely treats and disposes of sewage or
        solid waste.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15423 mb-requirement-id-15425">
        (2) Discuss your visit and what you learned with your counselor.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15423 mb-requirement-id-15426">
        (3) Describe how sewage and solid waste should be disposed of under
        wilderness camping conditions.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15422 mb-requirement-id-15427">
        (b) Visit a food service facility, such as a restaurant or school
        cafeteria.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15427 mb-requirement-id-15428">
        (1) Observe food preparation, handling, and storage. Learn how the
        facility keeps food from becoming contaminated.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15427 mb-requirement-id-15429">
        (2) Find out what conditions allow microorganisms to multiply in food,
        what can be done to help prevent them from growing and spreading, and
        how to kill them. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/_8s2FsT9VYY" target="_blank"
          >Food Safety: Meet Bacteria (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15427 mb-requirement-id-15430">
        (3) Discuss the importance of using a thermometer to check food
        temperatures. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/-2KkV2yFiN0" target="_blank"
          >The Importance of Cooking to a Safe Internal Temperature and How To
          Use a Food Thermometer (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15427 mb-requirement-id-15431">
        (4) Discuss your visit and what you learned with your counselor.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15432">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15432 mb-requirement-id-15433">
        (a) Describe the health dangers from air, water, and noise pollution.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/GVBeY1jSG9Y" target="_blank"
          >Breathe Life—How Air Pollution Impacts Your Body (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/FH3Vi5-UzlM" target="_blank"
          >8 Effects of Water Pollution on Our Health (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/5jfmzufa8qo" target="_blank"
          >Noise Pollution Is Much Worse for You Than You Think (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15432 mb-requirement-id-15434">
        (b) Describe health dangers from tobacco use and alcohol and drug abuse.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/wQl_4kcE5nw" target="_blank"
          >Teen Substance Use &amp; Abuse (Alcohol, Tobacco, Vaping, Marijuana,
          and More) (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9dZS_Rniak0" target="_blank"
          >Electronic Cigarettes and Vaping (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15432 mb-requirement-id-15435">
        (c) Describe the health dangers from abusing illegal and prescription
        drugs. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/b6Dte96WdqM" target="_blank"
          >Drug Abuse, Causes, Signs and Symptoms, Diagnosis and Treatment
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15436">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 7. </span>
      With your parent or guardian's and counselor's approval, do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15436 mb-requirement-id-15452">
        (a) Do ONE of the following
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15452 mb-requirement-id-15453">
        (1) Visit your city, county, state or federal public health agency.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.cdc.gov/public-health-gateway/php/communications-resources/health-department-directories.html"
          target="_blank"
          >Find Your Health Department (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15452 mb-requirement-id-15454">
        (2) Familiarize yourself with your city, county, state, or a federal
        health agency's website.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15436 mb-requirement-id-15440">
        (b) After completing either 7(a) do the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15440 mb-requirement-id-15441">
        (1) Compare the four leading causes of mortality (death) in your
        community for any of the past five years with the four leading causes of
        disease in your community. Explain how the public health agency you
        visited is trying to reduce the mortality and morbidity rates of these
        leading causes of illness and death. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/products/nvsr.htm" target="_blank"
          >National Vital Statistics System (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15440 mb-requirement-id-15442">
        (2) Explain the role of your health agency as it relates to the outbreak
        of diseases. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/zN58Uj1pxg4" target="_blank"
          >How Does Public Health Tackle Outbreaks? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15440 mb-requirement-id-15443">
        (3) Discuss the kinds of public assistance the agency is able to provide
        in case of disasters such as floods, storms, tornadoes, earthquakes, and
        other acts of destruction. Your discussion can include the cleanup
        necessary after the disaster. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Ml-bLyLE-_A" target="_blank"
          >FEMA's Role in Disaster Relief (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15447">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 8. </span>
      Pick a profession in the public health sector that interests you. Find out
      the education, training, and experience required to work in this
      profession. Discuss what you learn with your counselor. <br /><i
        >Resources:</i
      >
      <a href="https://youtu.be/FvN1rfxYKIo" target="_blank"
        >Career in Public Health| Everything You Need to Know Public Health
        Careers| Healthcare Management (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/QpaOGYDMe38" target="_blank"
        >Public Health Careers at the CDC (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/l-wciIH4FcQ" target="_blank"
        >Why Study Public Health? | College Majors | College Degrees (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
